and is intended to be omitted in the law.

SB 1247 2
17 prescribe controlled substances under a collaborative
18 practice arrangement under section 334.104 may prescribe any
19 controlled substances listed in Schedules III, IV, and V of
20 section 195.017, and may have restricted authority in
21 Schedule II. Prescriptions for Schedule II medications
22 prescribed by an advanced practice registered nurse who has
23 a certificate of controlled substance prescriptive authority
24 are restricted to only those medications containing
25 hydrocodone and Schedule II controlled substances for
26 hospice patients pursuant to the provisions of section
27 334.104. However, no such certified advanced practice
28 registered nurse shall prescribe controlled substance for
29 his or her own self or family. Schedule III narcotic
30 controlled substance and Schedule II - hydrocodone
31 prescriptions shall be limited to a one hundred twenty-hour
32 supply without refill.
33 3. A certified registered nurse anesthetist, as such
34 term is defined in section 335.016, may select, issue orders
35 for, and administer controlled substances listed in
36 Schedules II, III, IV, and V of section 195.017 for and
37 during the course of providing anesthesia care to a patient
38 in a licensed facility pursuant to state law. The
39 provisions of this subsection shall not be construed as
40 authorizing a certified registered nurse anesthetist to
41 prescribe such controlled substances. Notwithstanding any
42 other provision of law to the contrary, a certified
43 registered nurse anesthetist shall not be required to obtain
44 a certificate of controlled substance prescriptive authority
45 from the board of nursing under section 335.019 in order to
46 exercise the authority provided by this subsection.
47 4. A veterinarian, in good faith and in the course of
48 the veterinarian's professional practice only, and not for

SB 1247 3
49 use by a human being, may prescribe, administer, and
50 dispense controlled substances and the veterinarian may
51 cause them to be administered by an assistant or orderly
52 under his or her direction and supervision.
53 [4.] 5. A practitioner shall not accept any portion of
54 a controlled substance unused by a patient, for any reason,
55 if such practitioner did not originally dispense the drug,
56 except:
57 (1) When the controlled substance is delivered to the
58 practitioner to administer to the patient for whom the
59 medication is prescribed as authorized by federal law.
60 Practitioners shall maintain records and secure the
61 medication as required by this chapter and regulations
62 promulgated pursuant to this chapter; or
63 (2) As provided in section 195.265.
64 [5.] 6. An individual practitioner shall not prescribe
65 or dispense a controlled substance for such practitioner's
66 personal use except in a medical emergency.
